<font color="#FF0000">THE WALL</font><br>
<tt>Wed Nov 27 18:38:53 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
I was only 12 when the Vietnam War was declared over.  And my parents didn't have a TV when I was growing up, so since news about the war was so much disseminated via television, I didn't know a lot about it.<br><br>
I visited the Wall about five years ago.  I started at one end, and was reading each of the names as I walked along.  After just a few steps I started to cry, because I suddenly realized that all of the names I had read so far represented a small fraction of those that were on the Wall.  Seeing the whole Wall helped me understand just how many Americans died in the war.<br><br>
What I also realized, but that the Wall didn't represent (and probably wasn't meant to), that for every name on that wall there is a family and a set of friends who have lost someone.  And for everyone who did come back, there are scores more who did but who will be forever scarred.<br><br>
I have since read McNamara's book, and other books like Caputo's.  So I understand a little more, at least as much as books can tell you.<br><br>
-- Louise Penberthy<br>

